The Swimmer environment is a continuous-control task in which a chain of linked segments must move to the right by applying torques at two joints while minimizing unnecessary control effort.

The observation is a vector of {{ obs_dim }} values:
- state[0]: angle of the front tip
- state[1]: angle of the first rotor
- state[2]: angle of the second rotor
- state[3]: x-velocity of the tip
- state[4]: y-velocity of the tip
- state[5]: angular velocity of the front tip
- state[6]: angular velocity of the first rotor
- state[7]: angular velocity of the second rotor

The action is a vector of {{ action_dim }} continuous torques in the range [-1, 1].

The policy first computes {{ hidden_dim }} frozen nonlinear features using a random projection:
- hidden[j] = tanh(W_random[j] · state + b_random[j])

The first-layer weights W_random and biases b_random are fixed for the run and are not edited.
Before the random projection, each observation value is divided by {{ obs_scale }} and clipped to [-{{ obs_clip }}, {{ obs_clip }}] so the hidden features stay in a stable range.
You only optimize the trainable linear readout on top of these hidden features:
- action[k] = sum_j theta[k, j] * hidden[j] + bias[k]
- the final readout is scaled by {{ output_gain }} before being sent to the environment

This means the trainable params weight abstract nonlinear features rather than single raw observation dimensions.
Each trainable parameter should stay in the range [{{ param_min }}, {{ param_max }}].
